is  an involution  of ${\mathbb{F}}_q$  if and only if 
(i)  there exists integers  $g_i, t_i$ such that $r_i g_i + s t_i =1$ for any  $i=0, 1, \ldots, \ell-1$;
(ii)   $\{ \varphi(i) = ind_\gamma (A_i) + i r_i  \bmod \ell \mid i =0,\ldots, \ell-1\} = \mathbb{Z}_{\ell}$,  a complete set of residues modulo $\ell$;
(iii) $r_{\varphi(i)} \equiv r_i^{-1} \equiv g_i \pmod{s} $ for any $i=0, 1, \ldots, \ell-1$;
(iv) $A_{\varphi(i)} = A_i^{-g_i} \zeta^{it_i}$  for any $i=0, 1, \ldots, \ell-1$. 
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}
By Theorem~\ref{thm1},  $P$ is a PP if and only if (i) and (ii) are both satisfied. Moreover, $P(x) = P(x)^{-1}$ if and only if  $r_{\varphi(i)} \equiv  r_{\varphi(i)}^\prime \equiv r_i^{-1} \equiv g_i \pmod{s}$ and $ A_{\varphi(i)} = B_{\varphi(i)} = A_i^{-r_{\varphi(i)}^\prime} \gamma^{ist_i} = A_i^{-g_i} \zeta^{it_i} $. 
\end{proof}

